               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">LYDIA BROWN</hi>. I am the wife of James Brown. I hung out two shirts and a shift to dry on the 1st of Feb., about a quarter to six o'clock in the evening—I missed them directly, and followed the prisoner out of my place.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184402050169"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1148" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1148" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1148" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1148" type="given" value="WILLIAM HENRY"></interp>WILLIAM HENRY BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. On Thursday evening, the 1st of Feb. my mother was running after the prisoner—I ran too—there was another with the prisoner—the prisoner had a bundle, and he threw it to the other boy, who ran away—I saw the prisoner come out of our premises and turn the corner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440205-name-1149" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1149" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1149" type="surname" value="HAWKSWORTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440205-name-1149" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HAWKSWORTH</persName>
                  </hi>. I h eard a cry of "Stop thief"—I saw the prisoner running up the lane—he threw what looked to me like a bundle of clothes to another boy, and said, "<hi rend="italic">Cut away, Bill</hi>, across to the Britannia."</p>
